<br>
<br>
Medical-related Euthanasia:<br>
<br>
I am all for it. If a person, who has been given all the rights and privileges of an adult, is sane of mind and wishes to end their own life (for medical reasons), then he/she should be allowed to do so.<br>
<br>
Personal example here:<br>
<br>
My mother, age 49, contracted serious medical conditions brought about by arsenic poisoning (long story about how that happened not needed). It required her to be on oxygen and take medications for just about everything from waking up, to breathing, to going to sleep. It required her to retire early, be on state medical aid and wrack up huge hospital bills even after the insurance got through with it. To put it plain and simple, she was miserable and in pain all of the time. <br>
<br>
WHY IN THE HELL, should someone else have the right to tell her that she has to suffer the rest of her life, because it would be wrong to end her own life? When she died at the age of 51 (she suffocated on the way to the hospital... nice way to die huh?), I didn't cry because I was sad she died. I cried in happiness that she finally got to have her wish and end her suffering.<br>
<br>
If a person is sound of mind and chooses to end their life rather than be in suffering the rest of it, what kind of twisted society are we to say that they are *required* to suffer? <br>
<br>
We can enact the death penalty and give criminals the right to die via injection, but we make lawful members of our society endure pain and suffering?<br>
<br>
We can euthanize animals to end their pain and suffering, but not ourselves?<br>
<br>
/BOGGLE<br>
